__NOTOC__ '''Susanoo Jinja''' (素盞嗚神社、素戔嗚神社、素盞鳴神社、素戔鳴神社、須佐之男神社) is a Shinto shrine dedicated to {{ill|Gozu Tennō|ja|牛頭天王|1=Gozu Tennō|1=Gozu Tennō|12=draft|12=draft}} and {{ill|Susanoo|ja|スサノオ|12=draft|12=draft}}, central deities in {{ill|Gion Faith|ja|祇園信仰|12=draft|12=draft}}. Such shrines are located throughout Japan. Variations in the name include using "戔" instead of "盞" for the second character and "鳴 (with the bird radical)" instead of "嗚 (with the crow radical)" for the third character. Other shrines associated with Gion Faith include {{ill|Yasaka Shrine (disambiguation)|ja|八坂神社 (曖昧さ回避)|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|Gion Shrine|ja|祇園神社|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|Hiromine Shrine|ja|広峯神社|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|Tenno Shrine|ja|天王神社|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|Yakumo Shrine|ja|八雲神社|12=draft|12=draft}}, and {{ill|Suga Shrine|ja|須賀神社|12=draft|12=draft}}, which vary in usage across periods and sources.
Susanoo may also be written as 素盞雄, 須佐男, 須佐之男, 進雄, or 素盞雄, often with the addition of "命" (Mikoto) or "尊."
Until the Edo period, these shrines were generally referred to as '''Gozu Tennōsha''', venerating {{ill|Gozu Tennō|ja|牛頭天王|1=Gozu Tennō|1=Gozu Tennō|12=draft|12=draft}}. Their main shrines are located in Kyoto at {{ill|Yasaka Shrine|ja|八坂神社|12=draft|12=draft}} or in Hyōgo Prefecture at {{ill|Hiromine Shrine|ja|広峯神社|12=draft|12=draft}}.
== Kantō Region == * {{ill|Susanoo Shrine (Takasaki)|ja|進雄神社 (高崎市)|12=draft|12=draft}} (Gunma Prefecture, Takasaki) – Former Gōsha * {{ill|Susanoo Shrine (Hannō)|ja|素盞鳴神社 (飯能市)|12=draft|12=draft}} (Saitama Prefecture, Hannō) * {{ill|Susanoo Shrine (Arakawa)|ja|素盞雄神社 (荒川区)|12=draft|12=draft}} (Tokyo, Arakawa, Minamisenju) – Former Gōsha
